Job Title: Academic Oral and Maxillofacial Surgeon, DDS
Job Description:
Academic Oral and Maxillofacial Surgeon, DDS
The Department of Surgery at Harbor-UCLA Medical Center is seeking an academic surgeon for a full-time faculty position within the Division of Oral and Maxillofacial Surgery.
The position requires a DDS/DMD degree from a CODA-accredited U.S. or Canadian dental school and completion of a CODA-approved oral and maxillofacial surgery residency program. The candidate must be board- certified or board eligible by the American Board of Oral and Maxillofacial Surgery, and be eligible for an unrestricted California dental or medical license. An ideal candidate would have dual degree status, a strong interest in research and surgical education.
Harbor-UCLA Medical Center is a 531-bed, Los Angeles County Level I trauma center located in southwest Los Angeles and serves as a major teaching hospital for the UCLA School of Medicine. Responsibilities include clinical and surgical patient, didactic education and clinical teaching of residents and research. The position includes responsibilities at Harbor-UCLA Medical Center and Martin Luther King Jr Ambulatory Care Center. The candidate should have an interest in major oral and maxillofacial surgery with a particular interest in trauma management, is expected to actively participate in the clinical and research activities within the division, and be actively involved in resident training. Strong consideration will be given to candidates with demonstrated leadership and a commitment to caring for underserved populations.

Since it opened its doors in 1915, Henry Ford hospital has a reputation of providing for the growing needs of the community. From its 48-patient capacity start, growth and expansion throughout the last century has morphed Henry Ford Hospital into an 877-bed tertiary care center, Level I Trauma Center, and one of the largest teaching hospitals in the United States. Additionally, the institution has grown to include Henry Ford Allegiance, Macomb, Wyandotte, West Bloomfield, and Kingswood Hospitals, multiple specialty care services, community care services, and research and education initiatives. All told, currently the system provides 3.2 million patient visits annually.
Henry Ford previously had an impressive training program that has produced several leaders in our field. Who we are: La Clínica de La Raza is a community-based health center committed to providing culturally appropriate, high-quality, and accessible health care to the diverse communities of the San Francisco Bay Area. We have spent over 40 years advocating for and creating a health-home for the many that have been denied access to care. As health care activists, we are dedicated to ensuring that individuals who do not have healthcare coverage receive the same quality healthcare as those who do. From our genesis as a community health center in 1971, we understood that we cannot heal our communities without also addressing the economic and social factors that affect health. Many times, this requires that we go outside and provide services in other settings that link individuals to our health center for preventive and primary care. Over 90,000 individuals come to La Clínica because it is a welcoming place that addresses the whole person, coordinating and connecting them to a broad network of services to improve and maintain their health and well-being. While we are still known for our activism and spirit of social justice, we are also proud to have grown into a sophisticated provider of primary health care services with 35 sites across Alameda, Contra Costa and Solano counties.
